<ContentLayout
  eyebrow="About"
  title="What this site is"
  description="A private place for our growing family."
>
  <p>
    A guide through our little one's first year alongside a journal of moments as they
    happen. The site is password-protected and shared only with close family and friends.
  </p>

  <h2>The Baby Guide</h2>
  <p>
    The <a href="/guide/">guide</a> runs at two speeds, because babies do: a page for every
    week of the <a href="/weeks/">newborn stretch</a> (the first three months), then a page
    per <a href="/months/">month to the first birthday</a> — plus a
    <a href="/milestones/">milestone timeline</a> of the whole year and deep dives on the
    big topics like starting solids.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each page pulls together what seems to matter at that stage: milestones, feeding and
    sleep, safety, clear "when to call the doctor" signals, and honest picks on what's
    worth buying. Content is drawn from pediatric sources (Canadian Paediatric Society,
    AAP, Alberta Health Services, Health Canada, Nemours) and every claim links back to
    the page it came from.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is a personal record, not medical advice. If something feels wrong, call your
    pediatrician. Alberta Health Link is <strong>811</strong>; in an emergency call <strong>911</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>The journal</h2>
  <p>
    Short reflections and moments — captured loosely as they happen and polished into
    something readable. Written mostly for us, and for the small circle we're happy to
    share this with.
  </p>

  <h2>Leave a note</h2>
  <p>
    Every guide page has a "Notes from family" section at the bottom — if you've been
    through this stage before, we'd genuinely love your experience, tips, or product
    opinions. No account needed, just your name.
  </p>
</ContentLayout>
